The script had two major roles; both princes of a kingdom{{mdash}}the elder of whom was the hero and his brother the villain.{{Sfn|Guy|1997|p = 246}} M. K. Radha was offered the part of Sasankan, the younger prince.{{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page = 93}} As he was then known for playing heroic roles, he was unwilling to play a negative role,{{Sfn|Guy|1997|p = 246}} and instead agreed to play the older prince Veerasimhan.{{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page = 93}} Radha's wife had persuaded Vasan to cast Radha for the part.{{Sfn|Guy|1997|pp = 246<U+2013>247}} K. J. Mahadevan, who joined Gemini as a [[Production equipment control|production controller]], was chosen to play Sasankan,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/cinema-columns/aval-yaar-1957/article6136650.ece | title=Blast From The Past&nbsp;<U+2014> Aval Yaar (1957) | work=The Hindu | date=21 June 2014 | accessdate=4 July 2014 | last=Guy | first=Randor | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20140704122604/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/cinema-columns/aval-yaar-1957/article6136650.ece | archivedate=4 July 2014}}</ref> while T. G. Raghavachari agreed to direct the film.<ref name="madras musings" /> Some footage featuring Mahadevan was shot, but his performance was deemed "too soft" and he was dismissed from the part.{{Sfn|Guy|1997|p = 247}} He continued to serve as a scriptwriter and an assistant director.{{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page = 92}}<ref>''Chandralekha (Tamil) DVD''. Opening titles, at 1:23</ref> When Raghavachari suggested Ranjan for Sasankan, Vasan was reluctant, feeling he was too [[effeminacy|effeminate]] to play a "steel-hard villain", but eventually agreed. By then, Ranjan was already committed to B. N. Rao's ''[[Saalivaahanan]]'' (1945), but Kittoo persuaded him to take a [[screen test]] for ''Chandralekha'' and Rao gave Ranjan a few days off. The test was successful and Ranjan was officially cast.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hindu.com/cp/2011/06/26/stories/2011062650391600.htm | title=Blast from the Past&nbsp;<U+2014> Saalivaahanan 1945 | work=The Hindu | date=26 June 2011 | accessdate=20 September 2013 | last=Guy | first=Randor | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110704080547/http://www.hindu.com/cp/2011/06/26/stories/2011062650391600.htm | archivedate=20 September 2013}}</ref>

T. R. Rajakumari was chosen to play Chandralekha,<ref name="madras musings" /> replacing Vasan's first choice K. L. V. Vasantha.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/article1433352.ece | title=Remembering Vasantha | work=The Hindu | date=29 February 2008 | accessdate=13 August 2014 | last=Guy | first=Randor | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20140813133114/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/article1433352.ece | archivedate=13 August 2014}}</ref> Film historian [[Randor Guy]] believes Vasan chose Rajakumari over Vasantha because she was then leaving Gemini Studios permanently for [[Modern Theatres]] in [[Salem (India)|Salem]].<ref name="madras musings" /> In April 1947, N. S. Krishnan was released from prison;{{efn | N. S. Krishnan had been arrested on 28 December 1944 as a suspect in the [[Lakshmikanthan murder case]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/article73652.ece | title=Alleged celebrity crime in 1944 | work=[[The New Indian Express]] | date=24 August 2009 | accessdate=3 July 2013 | author=Gangadharan, V. | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130704035713/http://newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/article73652.ece | archivedate=4 July 2013}}</ref>|name = arrest}} Vasan recruited him and T. A. Madhuram to play the circus artists who help Veerasimhan rescue Chandralekha from Sasankan.<ref name="madras musings" /> The script was rewritten; new scenes were added to showcase the comedy duo.<ref name="the hindu" /> Actors Madurai Sriramulu Naidu and [[S. N. Lakshmi]] made their acting debut in this film; the former appears in an uncredited role as a horseman,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hindu.com/cp/2011/03/06/stories/2011030650391600.htm | title=Blast from the Past&nbsp;<U+2014> Madanamala 1948 | work=The Hindu | date=6 March 2011 | accessdate=23 April 2014 | last=Guy | first=Randor | archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6P2zmpt8N | archivedate=23 April 2014}}</ref> and the latter appears as a dancer in the climactic drum-dance scene.<ref name="Truthdive">{{cite web | url=http://truthdive.com/2012/02/20/tamil-actress-s-n-lakshmi-passes-away.html | title=Tamil actress S N Lakshmi passes away | publisher=TruthDive | date=20 February 2012 | accessdate=17 September 2013 | last=Devi | first=Kanchana | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20120221171609/http://truthdive.com/2012/02/20/tamil-actress-s-n-lakshmi-passes-away.html | archivedate=17 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/article790220.ece | title=Courage goaded her on&nbsp;... | work=The Hindu | date=28 May 2010 | accessdate=13 August 2014 | last=Rangarajan | first=Malathi | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/save/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/article790220.ece | archivedate=13 August 2014}}</ref>

When a minor role of the hero's bodyguard was yet to be cast, the then struggling stage actor Villupuram Chinniah Pillai Ganeshamurthy{{mdash}}who later became known as [[Sivaji Ganesan]]{{mdash}}was interested; he grew his hair long for the role. Ganeshamurthy had contacted Kittoo several times asking for a role in the film. Eventually, Kittoo took Ganeshamurthy to Vasan, who had seen him perform on-stage. To Ganeshamurthy's dismay, Vasan rejected him, calling him "totally unsuited for films" and told him to choose another profession. This incident caused a permanent schism between Vasan and Ganeshamurthy.<ref name="madras musings" /> The role of the bodyguard was eventually given to N. Seetharaman, who later became known as [[Javar Seetharaman]].{{Sfn|Guy|1997|p = 248}}

Kothamangalam Subbu's wife M. S. Sundari Bai plays a circus performer who helps Chandralekha escape from Sasankan.{{Sfn|Guy|1997|p = 248}} T. A. Jayalakshmi, in one of her earliest film roles, appears briefly in one scene that lasted for a few minutes, as a dancer.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/article2115563.ece | title=Blast from the past&nbsp;<U+2014> Pizhaikkum Vazhi (1948) | work=The Hindu | date=18 June 2011 | accessdate=9 September 2013 | last=Guy | first=Randor | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130909144452/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/article2115563.ece | archivedate=9 September 2013}}</ref>{{Sfn|Guy|1997|p = 152}} L. Narayana Rao plays the circus manager.{{Sfn|Guy|1997|p = 248}} T. E. Krishnamachari plays the king and V. N. Janaki plays a gypsy dancer who gives Chandralekha and Veerasimhan shelter in the forest.{{Sfn|Guy|1997|pp = 247<U+2013>248}} Veppathur Kittoo plays Sasankan's spy; he also worked as an assistant director in the film.{{Sfn|Guy|1997|p = 249}} Pottai Krishnamurthy appears in the song "Naattiya Kuthirai".<ref name="unsung"/> Other supporting actors include Seshagiri Bhagavathar, Appanna Iyengar, T. V. Kalyani, Surabhi Kamala, Subbiah Pillai, Cocanada Rajarathnam, N. Ramamurthi, Ramakrishna Rao, Sundara Rao, V. S. Susheela, Varalakshmi and Velayutham, in addition to "100 Gemini Boys & 500 Gemini Girls".<ref name="tamil credits" /> Studio staff members, their families and passers-by were recruited as extras to play spectators in the circus scenes.<ref name="the hindu" />

===Filming===
{{Quote box
 |quote = During the making (of ''Chan<U+00AD>dra<U+00AD>lekha''), our studio looked like a small kingdom&nbsp;... horses, elephants, lions, tigers in one corner, palaces here and there, over there a German lady training nearly a hundred dancers on one studio floor, a shapely Sinhalese lady teaching another group of dancers on real marble steps adjoining a palace, a <U+00AD>studio worker making weapons, another making period furniture using expensive rosewood, set props, headgear, and costumes, Ranjan undergoing fencing practice with our fight composer 'Stunt Somu', our music directors composing and rehearsing songs in a building&nbsp;... there were so many activities going on simultaneously round the clock.
 |source =&nbsp;<U+2013> Kothamangalam Subbu, on the making of the film at Gemini Studios{{Sfn|Guy|1997|p=247}}
 |align = right
 |width = 25.1%
 |border = 1px
}}
''Chandralekha'' began shooting in 1943.<ref name="Cecil" /> More than half of the film was directed by Raghavachari, but due to differences of opinion that arose between him and Vasan over the shooting of some scenes at the Governor's Estate (now [[Raj Bhavan (Chennai)|Raj Bhavan, Guindy]]),{{sfn|Guy|1997|p=249}} Raghavachari left the project and Vasan took over directing, making his directorial debut.<ref name="madras musings" />

Originally, the film did not include any circus scenes. Vasan decided to include them when the film was halfway through production, and the screenplay was altered.<ref name="the hindu" /> Kittoo travelled throughout South India and Ceylon (now [[Sri Lanka]]) to see over 50 circuses<ref name="madras musings" /> before choosing the Kamala Circus Company and Parasuram Lion Circus;<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.india-seminar.com/2013/651/651_s_theopore_baskaran.htm | title=The elephant in Tamil films | publisher=Seminar Publications, New Delhi | accessdate=3 February 2014 | author=[[S. Theodore Baskaran|Theodore Baskaran, S.]] | year=2013 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203155029/http://www.india-seminar.com/2013/651/651_s_theopore_baskaran.htm | archivedate=3 February 2014}}</ref> Vasan employed Kamala for a month.{{Sfn|Garga|2005|p = 119}} The circus scenes were shot by K. Ramnoth.<ref name="the hindu" /><ref name="forgotten" /> In retrospect, Kittoo said about Ramnoth's work, "In those days, we had no zoom lenses and yet Ramnoth did it. One night, while Chandralekha is performing on the flying trapeze, she notices the villain's henchman in the front row. She is on her perch high up and he is seated in a ringside chair. Shock hits her and to convey the shock the camera zooms fast from her to the man. Today, with a fast zoom shot it can be done very easily, but there was no such lens forty years ago. Ramnoth did it using the crane. He planned it well and rehearsed the shot for long. He took the shot 20 times and selected the best 'take'."{{Sfn|Guy|1997|p = 249}} The circus scenes lasted for 20 minutes; according to [[G. Dhananjayan]] these are "the longest footage of scenes outside the main plot that one can see".{{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page = 93}}

After Raghavachari's departure, one sequence he directed{{mdash}}the drum-dance scene{{mdash}}remained in the film.<ref name="forgotten">{{cite web | url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/the-forgotten-heroes/article5204125.ece | title=The forgotten heroes | work=The Hindu | date=5 October 2013 | accessdate=7 October 2013 | author=Guy, Randor | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20131005160804/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/the-forgotten-heroes/article5204125.ece | archivedate=7 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/chen-columns/doctor-savithri-1955/article3726984.ece | title=Blast from the Past&nbsp;<U+2014> Doctor Savithri: 1955 | work=The Hindu | date=4 August 2012 | accessdate=26 September 2013 | last=Guy | first=Randor | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130926155530/http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/chen-columns/doctor-savithri-1955/article3726984.ece | archivedate=26 September 2013}}</ref> The scene involved 400 dancers and six months of daily rehearsals. It was designed by the chief art director A. K. Sekhar,<ref name="madras musings" /> choreographed by Jayashankar<ref name="the hindu" /> and was shot with four cameras by Ellapa, C. V. Ramakrishnan, S. Maruthi Rao{{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page = 93}} and mainly Kamal Ghosh.<ref name="Rohini">{{cite web | url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/rohini-1953/article4322990.ece | title=Blast from the Past&nbsp;<U+2014> Rohini 1953 | work=The Hindu | date=19 January 2013 | accessdate=24 September 2013 | last=Guy | first=Randor | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130924151809/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/rohini-1953/article4322990.ece | archivedate=24 September 2013}}</ref> The drum dance alone cost {{INR}}{{formatnum:500000}} (about US$105,000 in 1948),{{efn| The exchange rate in 1948 was 4.79 Indian rupees ({{INR}}) per 1 US dollar (US$).<ref name="value">{{cite web | url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2013-08-24/news/41444029_1_indian-rupee-american-currency-continued-dollar-demand | title=Rupee's journey since Independence: Down by 65 times against dollar | work=[[The Economic Times]] | date=24 August 2013 | accessdate=29 August 2013 | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130829085318/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2013-08-24/news/41444029_1_indian-rupee-american-currency-continued-dollar-demand | archivedate=29 August 2013}}</ref>|name = exchange1948}} equal to the complete budget for a typical Indian film of the time.{{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|p = 93}}

During [[post-production]], Vasan asked Ramnoth his opinion of the scene in which hundreds of Veerasimhan's warriors storm the palace to rescue Chandralekha from Sasankan. Although everyone else praised the scene's photography, shots and action, Ramnoth remained quiet, finally saying that the suspense could be ruined if the scene was shown uncut, which sparked a discussion. Vasan advised the [[film editing|editor]] Chandru to edit according to Ramnoth, and he was impressed with the result.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2004/11/05/stories/2004110502700400.htm | title=What made Vasan different | work=The Hindu | date=5 November 2004 | accessdate=24 September 2013 | author=Krishnaswamy, N. | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20060302174810/http://www.hindu.com/fr/2004/11/05/stories/2004110502700400.htm | archivedate=24 September 2013}}</ref> C. E. Biggs worked as the [[sound engineer]].{{Sfn|Garga|2005|p = 117}}

''Chandralekha'' was in production for five years (from 1943 to 1948); it went through numerous changes to its story, cast, and filming. This caused substantial time and [[cost overrun]]s; the film ultimately cost {{INR}}3&nbsp;million (about US$600,000 in 1948),{{efn|name = exchange1948}} and became the most expensive Indian film at that time.<ref name="madras musings" /> Vasan had mortgaged all of his property, received financial assistance from [[K. Srinivasan|Sreenivasa Iyengar]]{{mdash}}then the editor of ''[[The Hindu]]''{{mdash}}and sold his jewellery to complete the film.<ref name="maalai malar">{{cite web | url=http://www.maalaimalar.com/2012/01/11114143/chandralekha-film-produced.html | title=<U+0BB0><U+0BC2>.30 <U+0BB2><U+0B9F><U+0BCD><U+0B9A><U+0BAE><U+0BCD> <U+0B9A><U+0BC6><U+0BB2><U+0BB5><U+0BBF><U+0BB2><U+0BCD> <U+0BA4><U+0BAF><U+0BBE><U+0BB0><U+0BBE><U+0BA9> <U+0B9A><U+0BA8><U+0BCD><U+0BA4><U+0BBF><U+0BB0><U+0BB2><U+0BC7><U+0B95><U+0BBE> | work=[[Maalai Malar]] | date=11 January 2012 | accessdate=7 April 2014 | language=Tamil | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120116123149/http://www.maalaimalar.com/2012/01/11114143/chandralekha-film-produced.html | archivedate=16 January 2012}}</ref> Adjusted for inflation, the film would have cost {{US$|28&nbsp;million}} in 2010.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.srilankaguardian.org/2010/06/star-trek-from-chintamani-to-vijay.html | title=The star trek from Chintamani to Vijay | work=The Sri Lanka Guardian | date=2 June 2010 | accessdate=9 September 2013 | last=Rajakarunanayake | first=Lucien | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20100828231158/http://www.srilankaguardian.org/2010/06/star-trek-from-chintamani-to-vijay.html | archivedate=9 September 2013}}</ref> According to film historian [[S. Muthiah]], ''Chandralekha'', considering the free-floating exchange rate at that time, became the first film with a budget of more than a million dollars to be made outside of the United States.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/mp/2003/12/08/stories/2003120800250300.htm | title=When the postman knocked | work=The Hindu | date=8 December 2003 | accessdate=11 August 2014 | author=Muthiah, S. | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20140813064934/http://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/mp/2003/12/08/stories/2003120800250300.htm | archivedate=13 August 2014}}</ref>

==Themes and influences==
Although a period film, ''Chandralekha'' is not based on historical fact;{{Sfn|Dwyer|Patel|2002|p = 144}} instead its plot is based on the first chapter of the novel ''Robert Macaire: or, The French bandit in England''. Sasankan is based on the fictional bandit [[Robert Macaire]],{{Sfn|Guy|1997|p = 246}} and Chandralekha is based on a female dancer in the novel who Macaire flogs when she refuses to dance.{{Sfn|Garga|2005|p = 118}} The film enacts the incident from the novel.<ref name="the hindu" /> According to film historian B. D. Garga, the film also shows influences from other Western literary and cinematic sources, including the novel ''[[Sangre y arena|Blood and Sand]]'' (1908), and the films ''[[The Mark of Zorro (1920 film)|The Mark of Zorro]]'' (1920), ''[[Robin Hood (1922 film)|Robin Hood]]'' (1922), ''[[The Thief of Bagdad (1924 film)|The Thief of Baghdad]]'' (1924) and ''[[Ben-Hur (1925 film)|Ben-Hur]]'' (1925).{{Sfn|Garga|2005|p = 118}} In December 1964, [[Jerzy Toeplitz]] called ''Chandralekha'' an "extension and development" of the mythology genre. Toeplitz said, "The characters are mortals but behave like heavenly beings, and their movements and gestures, like those of the gods and heroes of the ''[[Mahabharata]]'' are impregnated with the miraculous". He called the story a "mere pretext to hold together the different episodes, each of which builds up like a circus turn: the tension mounts to a culminating point, whereupon the next episode immediately takes over".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0013/001341/134149eo.pdf | title=Indian films and Western audiences | publisher=[[UNESCO]] | date=23 December 1964 | accessdate=4 August 2014 | author=[[Jerzy Toeplitz|Toeplitz, Jerry]] | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20120208164919/http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0013/001341/134149eo.pdf | archivedate=8 February 2012}}</ref> According to the book ''Third World Film Making and the West'' (1987) by Roy Armes, [[Uday Shankar]]'s ''[[Kalpana (1948 film)|Kalpana]]'' (1948), which was also shot at Gemini Studios, inspired Vasan to make ''Chandralekha''.{{Sfn|Armes|1987|pp = 114<U+2013>115}} In the 2003 book ''Encyclopaedia of Hindi Cinema'', ''Chandralekha'' is defined as a "[[Ruritanian romance|Ruritanian]] period extravaganza".{{Sfn|Gulaz<U+0101>ra|Nihalani|Chatterjee|2003|loc = [http://books.google.co.in/books?id=8y8vN9A14nkC&pg=PT456&lpg=PT456&dq=chandralekha+ruritanian&source=bl&ots=rwWu1fwnj7&sig=P_VFZm8G71pZnQX5QGC2qYzCk0U&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ox0LUqn1HoWjkQW6oICABw&ved=0CDQQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=chandralekha%20ruritanian&f=false p. 432]}}

The climactic sword fight between Veerasimhan and Sasankan has often been compared to that in the 1894 novel ''[[The Prisoner of Zenda]]''.{{Sfn|Banerjee|Srivastava|1988|p = 59}}{{Sfn|Raghavendra|2009|p = 34}} In 1976, American film historian [[William K. Everson]] compared the comedians in ''Chandralekha'' to the comedy duo [[Laurel and Hardy]].<ref name="everson" /> Although G. Dhananjayan and Randor Guy consider the film's drum dance scene as the first of its kind in Indian cinema,{{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|p = 93}}{{Sfn|Guy|1997|p = 249}} the 1947 film ''[[Naam Iruvar]]'' includes a scene in which the lead actress' younger sister dances on drums to the Tamil poet [[Subramania Bharati]]'s song "Kottu Murase";<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.upperstall.com/people/av-meiyappan | title=AV Meiyappan | publisher=[[Upperstall.com]] | accessdate=26 July 2014 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429224208/http://upperstall.com/people/av-meiyappan | archivedate=29 April 2014}}</ref>{{Sfn|Baskaran|1996|p = 102}} French film historian Yves Thoraval said this "prefigured the dance that ''Chandralekha'' made famous the very next year".{{Sfn|Thoraval|2000|p = 39}} According to American film critic [[Jonathan Rosenbaum]], ''Chandralekha'' "belongs to the same childhood continuum" as [[Fritz Lang]]'s 1959 films ''[[The Tiger of Eschnapur (1959 film)|The Tiger of Eschnapur]]'' and ''[[The Indian Tomb (1959 film)|The Indian Tomb]]'' which were set in India.<ref name="Rosenbaum" /> In his 2009 book '' 50 Indian Film Classics'', film critic M. K. Raghavendra states that ''Chandralekha'' is constructed in a manner that "enables its narrative to incorporate elements drawn from virtually any kind of genre".{{Sfn|Raghavendra|2009|p = 34}} According to Guy, the settings of the song "Naattiya Kuthirai" picturised on Sundari Bai's character, including the dance and the costume worn by Sundari Bai, are inspired by those seen in the 1943 musical film ''[[Coney Island (1943 film)|Coney Island]]''.<ref name="sundari bai" />

==Music==
The film's soundtrack was composed by [[S. Rajeswara Rao]],<ref name="1:43" /> with lyrics by [[Papanasam Sivan]] and Kothamangalam Subbu.<ref name="indolink" /> R. Vaidyanathan and B. Das Gupta collaborated with M. D. Parthasarathy on the background music.<ref name="1:43">''Chandralekha (Tamil) DVD''. Opening titles, at 1:43</ref> The music was influenced by [[Carnatic music|Carnatic]] music, [[Hindustani classical music|Hindustani]] music, [[Latin American music|Latin American]] and [[Portuguese folk music#Folk music|Portuguese folk music]], and [[Johann Strauss I]]'s waltzes.{{Sfn|Rajadhyaksha|Willemen|1999|p = 310}}{{Sfn|Garga|2005|p = 120}}<ref name="Bhaktavatsala"/> M. K. Raghavendra said the film has "snatches from [[Richard Wagner|Wagner]] and [[Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov|Rimsky Korsakov]] (''[[Scheherazade (Rimsky-Korsakov)|Scherezade]]'') being used at dramatic moments".{{Sfn|Raghavendra|2009|p = 34}}

The song "Naattiya Kuthirai" was not originally part of the script; it was added during the final stages of the film's production. Sundari Bai spent over a month rehearsing the song.<ref name="sundari bai">{{cite web | url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/article3217609.ece | title=Charming, villainous | work=The Hindu | date=24 March 2006 | accessdate=15 August 2014 | last=Guy | first=Randor | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20140815162422/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/article3217609.ece | archivedate=15 August 2014}}</ref> The songs "Indrae Enathu Kuthukalam" and "Manamohana Saaranae" were sung by T. R. Rajakumari,{{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page = 93}} while "Aathoram Kodikkalam" and "Naattiya Kuthirai" were sung by M. D. Parthasarathy.<ref name="unsung">{{cite web | url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/unsung-veteran-of-tamil-cinema/article786500.ece | title=Unsung veteran of Tamil cinema | work=The Hindu | date=23 September 2010 | accessdate=18 August 2013 | last=Guy | first=Randor | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130805052123/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/unsung-veteran-of-tamil-cinema/article786500.ece | archivedate=18 August 2013}}</ref> The circus chorus was adapted from "The Donkey Serenade" from [[Robert Z. Leonard]]'s ''[[The Firefly (film)|The Firefly]]'' (1937).{{Sfn|Rajadhyaksha|Willemen|1999|p = 310}}{{Sfn|Baskaran|1996|p = 60}} For the Hindi soundtrack, Vasan offered most of the songs to Uma Devi, who became popularly known as [[Tun Tun]].  She was initially hesitant, feeling that "these were beyond her capabilities", but she was supported by Rajeswara Rao who "worked hard on her".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2003/20031207/spectrum/main6.htm | title=Hindi cinema's first-ever comedienne | work=[[Tribune India]] | date=7 December 2003 | accessdate=24 July 2014 | last=Kaur | first=Devinder Bir | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130901001054/http://www.tribuneindia.com/2003/20031207/spectrum/main6.htm | archivedate=1 September 2013}}</ref> The music of ''Chandralekha'' helped it to become one of the most successful Indian musical films of the 1940s;{{Sfn|Vijayakar|2009|p = 16}} it "created an atmosphere for a number of music directors influenced by Western music" in Tamil cinema.<ref name="religion">{{cite book | url=http://books.google.co.in/books?id=rQoqAAAAYAAJ&q=chandraleka+donkey+serenade&dq=chandraleka+donkey+serenade&hl=en&sa=X&ei=9r_bUdOQCsqOrgedooDwDw&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAQ | title=Religion and Society, Volume 12 | publisher=Christian Institute for the Study of Religion and Society | year=1965 | page=103}}</ref>

In his 1997 book ''Starlight, Starbright: The Early Tamil Cinema'', Randor Guy said Partha<U+00AD>sarathy and Rajeswara Rao "created a fine blend of lilting music of many schools".{{Sfn|Guy|1997|p = 250}} Writing for ''[[Screen (magazine)|Screen]]'' in April 1998, film historian M. Bhaktavatsala called the songs as "distinct and standing on its own, with barely any background score attempting to interlink anything, just periods of silence".<ref name="Bhaktavatsala">{{cite journal | title=Music in the Movies | date=24 April 1998 | author=Bhaktavatsala, M. | journal=[[Screen (magazine)|Screen]] | page=p. 36}}</ref>

