==Marketing==
The first advertisement for ''Chandralekha'' appeared on the back cover of the songbook for the film ''[[Dasi Aparanji]]'' (1944). It featured Vasantha as the heroine, before she was replaced by Rajakumari.<ref name="the hindu" />{{efn | Although [[S. Muthiah]] said the film's first announcement came in 1943,<ref name="Cecil" /> Randor Guy said in his book ''Starlight, Starbright'' that an early advertisement for ''Chan<U+00AD>dra<U+00AD><U+00AD>lekha'' appeared on the inside cover of the ''[[Nandanar (film)|Nandanar]]'' songbook, which was published in September 1942.{{Sfn|Guy|1997|p=248}}|name = advertisement}} With ''Chandralekha'', Gemini became the first Tamil studio to attempt to distribute a film throughout India.<ref name="indolink">{{cite web | url=http://www.indolink.com/tamil/cinema/Memories/98/fna/fna3.htm | title=Tamil Cinema History&nbsp;<U+2014> The Early Days: 1945<U+2013>1953 | publisher=Indolink | accessdate=27 June 2013 | author="Film News" Anandan | year=1998 | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20120712005710/http://www.indolink.com/tamil/cinema/Memories/98/fna/fna3.htm | archivedate=27 June 2013}}</ref> According to film scholar P. K. Nair, ''Chandralekha'' was the first Indian film to have a full-page newspaper advertisement.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/b-town-rewind-the-tale-of-the-first-bollywood-crore/15162064 | title=B-Town rewind: The tale of the first Bollywood crore | work=[[Mid Day]] | date=16 March 2014 | accessdate=17 September 2014 | last=Unny | first=Divya | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316114251/http://www.mid-day.com/articles/b-town-rewind-the-tale-of-the-first-bollywood-crore/15162064 | archivedate=16 March 2014}}</ref> According to a 2010 article in ''[[Mumbai Mirror]]'' by Vishwas Kulkarni, {{INR}}574,500 was spent on newspaper publicity and {{INR}}642,300 on posters, banners and billboards.<ref name="mumbai mirror" /> G. Dhananjayan's book ''The Best of Tamil Cinema'' (2011) contradicts this, saying that Vasan spent close to {{INR}}500,000 on publicity alone.{{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page = 93}} ''Chandralekha'''s publicity campaign was the most expensive for an Indian film at that time; the entire publicity budget of a typical Indian film a decade earlier was around {{INR}}25,000. In the 1950s, the entire publicity for a "top Indian film" cost no more than {{INR}}100,000, which is substantially less than the amount spent on ''Chandralekha''.<ref name="mumbai mirror">{{cite web | url=http://www.mumbaimirror.com/others/sunday-read/When-illusions-were-painted/articleshow/16009611.cms | title=When illusions were painted | work=[[Mumbai Mirror]] | date=18 April 2010 | accessdate=25 April 2014 | last=Kulkarni | first=Vishwas | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140425064529/http://www.mumbaimirror.com/others/sunday-read/When-illusions-were-painted/articleshow/16009611.cms? | archivedate=25 April 2014}}</ref> According to Guy, the publicity campaign "made the nation sit up and take notice".{{Sfn|Guy|1997|p = 250}}

A. K. Shekhar designed the publicity material, which included posters, booklets and full-page newspaper advertisements. Gemini Studios, inspired by American cinema, also produced a publicity brochure for distribution to exhibitors and the press.{{Sfn|Dwyer|Patel|2002|p = 144}} It contained a synopsis of the film and a step pictorial account of the key points of the narrative. It provided text for use by local theatres. The booklet also had layouts for women's pages and a pictorial account of suggested marketing activities, such as "How to drape an Indian sari: Theatre demonstrations have a big draw", and information about the film's costumes{{mdash}}which were hand-woven garments of silk and gold; one gold-embroidered riding jacket is considered "the most expensive piece of outfitting ever used in a motion picture".{{Sfn|Dwyer|Patel|2002|pp = 144<U+2013>145}}

==Reception==

===Release===
''Chandralekha'' was released on 9 April 1948.<ref name="release">{{cite journal | url=http://books.google.com/?id=zJjDHHkTlbEC&q=chandraleka+1948&dq=chandraleka+1948 | title=Chandraleka | author=Natesan, G. A. | journal=The Indian Review | year=1948 | volume=49 | page=p. 333}}</ref> It was released simultaneously in 40 theatres throughout South India and in another 10 within a week.{{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page = 93}} In the 1940s, a typical Tamil film would be released in about 10 towns, but ''Chandralekha'' was released simultaneously in 120 towns.<ref name="maalai malar" />

''Chandralekha'' was released in Japan as ''Shakunetsu-no ketto'' ("Fight Under the Red Heat") in April 1954, where it was distributed by Nippon Cinema Corporation (NCC).<ref name="Japan" /> It was the first Tamil film to be dubbed in Japanese,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/did-you-know-/Rajinis-Muthu-wasnt-the-first-Tamil-film-in-Japanese/articleshow/34884747.cms | title=Rajini's Muthu wasn't the first Tamil film in Japanese | work=The Times of India | date=10 May 2014 | accessdate=19 May 2014 | archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6PgIW7iyk | archivedate=19 May 2014}}</ref> and the second Indian film to be released in Japan{{mdash}}the first was the 1952 [[Bollywood|Hindi]] film ''[[Aan]]'', which was released in Tokyo in January 1954. NCC later collapsed; no information about how ''Chandralekha'' came to be released in Japan survives. During the 1950s, when India was short of foreign currency, barter was a common means of exchange with overseas business partners. Japanese scholar Tamaki Matsuoka believes this to have been the case with ''Chandralekha''. The pamphlet prepared by NCC for the film calls Vasan the "[[Cecil B. DeMille]] of the Indian film industry".<ref name="Japan">{{cite book | url=http://ir.minpaku.ac.jp/dspace/bitstream/10502/1140/1/SES71_011.pdf | title=Asia to Watch, Asia to Present: The Promotion of Asian/Indian Cinema in Japan | publisher=Senri Ethnological Studies, Reitaku University | last=Matsuoka | first=Tamaki | year=2008 | format=PDF | page=246 | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110722073202/http://ir.minpaku.ac.jp/dspace/bitstream/10502/1140/1/SES71_011.pdf | archivedate=18 August 2013}}</ref> A Danish version of the film titled ''Indiens hersker'' ("India's ruler"), was released on 26 April 1954.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dfi.dk/faktaomfilm/film/en/16471.aspx?id=16471 | title=Indiens hersker | work=Danish Film Institute | accessdate=17 July 2013 | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130717084315/http://www.dfi.dk/faktaomfilm/film/en/16471.aspx?id=16471 | archivedate=17 July 2013}}</ref> An abridged English-language version of ''Chandralekha'', titled ''Chandra'', was screened in the United States and Europe during the 1950s.<ref name="Cecil" /><ref name="deccan herald">{{cite web | url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/103530/decoding-rajinikanth.html | title=Decoding Rajinikanth | work=[[Deccan Herald]] | date=28 July 2011 | accessdate=18 September 2013 | author=Venkatesh, M. R. | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110728135431/http://www.deccanherald.com/content/103530/decoding-rajinikanth.html | archivedate=18 September 2013}}</ref>

The film was a [[bellwether]] for its filming, production costs and publicity before, during and after its release. Other producers delayed releasing their films until after ''Chandralekha''{{'}}s release to avoid competition. The film's entertainment value made it popular with audiences;{{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page = 94}} however, it was unable to recover its production costs, and Vasan remade it in Hindi in order to do so.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.timescrest.com/culture/southern-stars-shine-bright-in-the-north-10631 | title=Southern stars shine bright in the north | work=[[The Times of India|Times Crest]] | date=29 June 2013 | accessdate=6 August 2014 | last=Soman | first=Sandhya | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113131305/http://www.timescrest.com/culture/southern-stars-shine-bright-in-the-north-10631 | archivedate=13 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2011/20110703/spectrum/main8.htm | title=Southern splendour | work=The Tribune | date=3 July 2011 | accessdate=15 September 2014 | author=Gangadhar, V. | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712234724/http://www.tribuneindia.com/2011/20110703/spectrum/main8.htm | archivedate=12 July 2011}}</ref> The Hindi version was released the same year{{efn|[[Bollywood Hungama]] and IBOS Network give the Hindi version's release date as 1 January 1948.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/cast/id/539051 | title=Chandralekha (1948) | publisher=[[Bollywood Hungama]] | accessdate=9 July 2014 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130902214631/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/cast/id/539051 | archivedate=2 September 2013}}</ref><ref name="ibos">{{cite web | url=http://ibosnetwork.com/asp/actualalltime_worldwide.asp | title=All Time Worldwide Box Office Grossers of Indian Cinema | publisher=IBOS Network | accessdate=3 October 2013 | archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6K8Rag7t9 | archivedate=5 October 2013}}</ref> The date is erroneous; the Tamil version was released in April 1948. Its initially low box-office collections prompted Vasan to make a Hindi version.}} with over 600 prints{{efn|According to [[G. Dhananjayan]] and ''The Times of India'', the film was released with 609 prints worldwide;{{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page=93}}<ref>{{cite web | url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-09-10/did-you-know-/33736249_1_film-s-s-vasan-financial-budget | title=Costliest film in Kollywood! | work=The Times of India | date=10 September 2012 | accessdate=22 September 2013 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130922052103/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-09-10/did-you-know-/33736249_1_film-s-s-vasan-financial-budget | archivedate=22 September 2013}}</ref> other sources say it was released with 603 prints.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.upperstall.com/people/ss-vasan | title=SS Vasan | publisher=[[Upperstall.com]] | accessdate=21 November 2013 | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130805174537/http://upperstall.com/people/ss-vasan | archivedate=21 November 2013}}</ref>{{Sfn|Baskaran|1996|p=203}}}} and became a large commercial success, setting box-office records.{{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page = 93}} ''Chandralekha'' thus became the first production from Madras (now [[Chennai]]){{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page = 92}} and the first Indian film to become a hit throughout India.<ref name="a to z" /> Vasan called the film "a pageant for our peasants"{{Sfn|Chander|2003|p = 135}} meant for "the war-weary public that had been forced to watch insipid war propaganda pictures for years".{{Sfn|Ranade|2006|p = 127}} It was selected by the government of India for exhibition at the Fourth International Film Festival in [[Prague]] in 1949.<ref>{{cite book | url=http://books.google.co.in/books?id=qn9ZAAAAMAAJ&q=chandralekha+prague&dq=chandralekha+prague&hl=en&sa=X&ei=gHYfUqTgIs6Srge2-YDgAw&ved=0CDoQ6AEwAw | title=The Indian film | publisher=Greenwood Press | last=Shah | first=Panna | year=1950 | pages=83, 278}}</ref> The film's success made Madras a major production centre for Hindi films.{{Sfn|Vijayakar|2009|p = 15}} Five years after the film's success, Gemini paid its employees a bonus, becoming one of the first studios in the world to do so.{{Sfn|Baskaran|2009|p = 104}}

===Box office===
Although exact figures for the film's box office earnings are not available, film trade websites provide estimates of its takings. According to Sharmishtha Gooptu's 2010 book ''Bengali Cinema: An Other Nation'', ''Chandralekha'' grossed {{INR}}10 million (about US$2,100,000 in 1948){{efn|name = exchange1948}} in India alone.{{Sfn|Gooptu|2010|p = 133}} [[Box Office India]] gives the Hindi version's nett gross as {{INR}}7&nbsp;million and states that it was the second-highest-grossing Bollywood film of 1948 after ''[[Shaheed (1948 film)|Shaheed]]''.<ref name="BOI">{{cite web | url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=153&catName=MTk0OA== | title=Box Office 1948 | publisher=[[Box Office India]] | accessdate=13 August 2013 | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20121012171051/http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=153&catName=MTk0OA== | archivedate=13 August 2013}}</ref>{{efn|According to the website Box Office India, film tickets are subject to "entertainment tax" in India, and this tax is added to the ticket price at the box office window of theatres. The amount of this tax is variable among [[States and territories of India]]. "Nett gross figures are always after this tax has been deducted while gross figures are before this tax has been deducted." Although since 2003 the entertainment tax rate has significantly decreased, as of 2010, gross earnings of a film can be 30<U+2013>35% higher than nett gross, depending on the states where the film is released.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=315&catName=UmVhZCBNb3Jl |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020180004/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=315&catName=UmVhZCBNb3Jl |archivedate=20 October 2013 |title=Box Office in India Explained |publisher=Box Office India |accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref>|name = nettgross}} It gives its adjusted nett gross as {{INR}}37,98,00,000.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=121&catName=MTk0MC0xOTQ5&PHPSESSID=e0fa8771b933a7ecb56db5e4edc6d700 | title=Top Earners 1940<U+2013>1949 | publisher=Box Office India | accessdate=27 August 2014 | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20090214215339/http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=121&catName=MTk0MC0xOTQ5&PHPSESSID=e0fa8771b933a7ecb56db5e4edc6d700 | archivedate=14 February 2009}}</ref> Film historian B. D. Garga said in his 2005 book ''Art Of Cinema'', "The two versions{{mdash}}Tamil and Hindi{{mdash}}grossed millions".{{Sfn|Garga|2005|p = 118}} According to the 1998 book ''Indian cinema: A Visual Voyage'' by India's [[Ministry of Information and Broadcasting (India)|Ministry of Information and Broadcasting]], the film grossed {{INRConvert|20|m|year=1948|nolink=yes}} at the box office.{{Sfn|''Indian cinema: A Visual Voyage''|1998|p = 103}} A 2011 article by Namrata Joshi in ''[[Outlook (magazine)|Outlook India]]'' says, "''Chandralekha'' grossed Rs 1.55 crore with an audience of 3 crore, 60% from rural India."<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article/Reeling-It-All-In/278248 | title=Reeling It All In | work=Outlook India | date=19 September 2011 | accessdate=19 September 2014 | last=Joshi | first=Namrata | archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6ShYBJC0d | archivedate=19 September 2014}}</ref>

===Critical response===

====India====
[[File:Chandralekha drum dance scene.jpg|thumbnail|250px|right|alt=Several women dancing on giant drums.|The drum dance scene is often considered the highlight of the film by critics.]]
''Chandralekha'' received generally positive reviews from Indian critics. On 9 April 1948, ''The Hindu'' said, "India has not witnessed a film of this magnitude in terms of making and settings so far".{{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page = 94}} On 10 April, ''[[The Indian Express]]'' said, "''Chandralekha'' is an entertaining film for everyone with elements like animals, rope dance, circus and comedy".{{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page = 94}} The same day, the Tamil newspaper ''[[Dinamani]]'' said, "''Chandralekha'' is not only a first rate Tamil film but also an international film".{{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page = 94}}

[[V. A. K. Ranga Rao]] described the film as "the most complete entertainer ever made".{{efn|The comment by Ranga Rao appears in Randor Guy's 1997 book ''Starlight, Starbright: The Early Tamil Cinema''. The year of the comment is not mentioned.{{Sfn|Guy|1997|p=244}}}} In their 1988 book ''One Hundred Indian Feature Films: An Annotated Filmography'', Anil Srivastava and Shampa Banerjee praised nearly every aspect of the film, including its grandeur, the battle scenes and the drum dance, which they called the "''raison d'etre''" of the film.{{Sfn|Banerjee|Srivastava|1988|p = 59}} In 2003, journalist S. Muthiah called it "an epic extravaganza worthy of Cecil B. de. Mille" that was "larger-than-life".<ref name="twins">{{cite web | url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2003/11/26/stories/2003112600690300.htm | title=Sign of the Twins | work=The Hindu | date=26 November 2003 | accessdate=20 September 2013 | author=[[S. Muthiah|Muthiah, S.]] | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20040602150234/http://www.hindu.com/mp/2003/11/26/stories/2003112600690300.htm | archivedate=20 September 2013}}</ref> In their 2008 book ''Global Bollywood: Travels of Hindi Song and Dance'', Sangita Gopal and Sujata Moorti said, "''Chandralekha'' is a film that translates the aesthetic of Hollywood [[Orientalism]] for an indigenous mass audience", calling its drum-dance sequence "perhaps one of the most spectacular sequences in Indian cinema".{{Sfn|Gopal|Moorti|2008|p = 26}} In his 2009 book ''50 Indian Film Classics'', M. K. Raghavendra said, "Indian films are rarely constructed in a way that makes undistracted viewing essential to their enjoyment and ''Chandralekha'' is arranged as a series of distractions". He concluded by saying, "''Chandralekha'' apparently shows us that enjoyment and visual pleasure in the Indian context are not synonymous with edge-of-the-seat excitement but must permit absent-mindedness as a viewing condition".{{Sfn|Raghavendra|2009|p = 36}}

In May 2010, Raja Sen of [[Rediff.com]] praised the film's "grandly mounted setpieces", its "memorable drum dance" and the "longest swordfight ever captured on film", calling ''Chandralekha'' "just the kind of film, in fact, that would be best appreciated now after digital restoration".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-classics-to-be-restored/20100511.htm#4 | title=Ten Indian classics craving digital restoration | publisher=[[Rediff.com]] | date=11 May 2010 | accessdate=10 November 2013 | last=Sen | first=Raja | page=4 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008014445/http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-classics-to-be-restored/20100511.htm | archivedate=10 November 2013}}</ref> In an October 2010 review of ''Chandralekha'', Randor Guy praised Rajakumari's performance, calling it "her career-best" and saying that she "carried the movie on her shoulders". Guy praised Radha as his "usual impressive self", saying the film would be "remembered for: the excellent onscreen narration, the magnificent sets and the immortal drum dance sequence".<ref name="the hindu" /> In his 2011 book ''The Best of Tamil Cinema, 1931 to 2010: 1931<U+2013>1976'', G. Dhananjayan called the film "a delight to watch even after 50 years",{{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page = 93}} though he criticised the script.{{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page = 94}} In 2013, director Dhanapal Padmanabhan told K. Jeshi of ''The Hindu'', "''Chandralekha'' had grandeur that was at par with Hollywood standards".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/the-uninvited/article4689203.ece | title=The uninvited | work=The Hindu | date=6 May 2013 | accessdate=2 July 2013 | author=Jeshi, K. | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130702055701/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/the-uninvited/article4689203.ece | archivedate=2 July 2013}}</ref>

====Overseas====
''Chandralekha'' was well received by critics overseas. Reviewing the English version, ''[[The New York Times]]'' described Rajakumari as a "buxom beauty".{{efn|The comment by ''The New York Times'' appears in the August 2007 issue of the magazine ''Galatta Cinema''. The year of the comment is not mentioned.<ref>{{cite journal | url=http://i1303.photobucket.com/albums/ag149/kailash29792/75yearsoftamilcinemagalattacinema2_zpsaaba1881.jpg?t=1382155460 | title=From Silents to Sivaji! A look into the past&nbsp;<U+2014> Part II | date=August 2007 | last=Guy | first=Randor | publisher=Galatta Cinema | page=p. 68}}</ref>}} When ''Chandralekha'' was screened in New York City in 1976, William K. Everson said, "It's a colorful, naive and zestful film in which the overall ingenuousness quite disarms criticism of plot absurdity or such production shortcomings as the too-obvious studio "exteriors". [...] Last but far from least, [[Busby Berkeley]] would surely have been delighted to see his influence extending to the climactic drum dance."<ref name="everson">{{cite web | url=http://bampfa.berkeley.edu/film/FN2318 | title=Spectacle, Music & Action! | work=[[Berkeley Art Museum and Pacific Film Archive]] | accessdate=20 September 2013 | year=1981 | archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6JyKhiCAE | archivedate=28 September 2013}}</ref>

Jonathan Rosenbaum said in August 1981, "The prospect of a three-hour Indian film in {{Sic|Temil}} with no subtitles is a little off-putting, I would say{{mdash}}wouldn't you?"  However, he had "surprisingly little trouble following the plot and action" of the film, and added, "this made-in-Madras costume drama makes for a pretty action-packed 186 minutes."<ref name="Rosenbaum">{{cite web | url=http://www.jonathanrosenbaum.net/1981/08/august-humor/ | title=August Humor | publisher=Jonathanrosenbaum.net | date=20 August 1981 | accessdate=18 July 2013 | author=[[Jonathan Rosenbaum|Rosenbaum, Jonathan]] | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131008233351/http://www.jonathanrosenbaum.net/1981/08/august-humor/ | archivedate=18 July 2013}}</ref> In June 2009, K. S. Sivakumaran of ''[[Daily News (Sri Lanka)|Daily News Sri Lanka]]'' called it "the first colossal {{Sic|Thamil}} film I saw".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2009/06/08/fea21.asp | title=Indian film music: An amalgam of different tunes | work=[[Daily News (Sri Lanka)]] | date=8 June 2009 | accessdate=8 July 2013 | author=Sivakumaran, K. S. | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130708081641/http://www.dailynews.lk/2009/06/08/fea21.asp | archivedate=8 July 2013}}</ref> In October 2013, Malaysian author D. Devika Bai, writing for ''[[New Straits Times]]'', praised ''Chandralekha'' for its technical aspects; she said, "at almost 68, I have not tired of watching the movie".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nst.com.my/life-times/live/enduring-romance-with-the-west-1.385022 | title=Enduring romance with the West | work=[[New Straits Times]] | date=26 October 2013 | accessdate=3 November 2013 | author=Devika Bai, D. | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101051006/http://www.nst.com.my/life-times/live/enduring-romance-with-the-west-1.385022 | archivedate=3 November 2013}}</ref>

=={{anchor|Differences}}Hindi version==
The Hindi version of ''Chandralekha'' was Vasan's first Bollywood project.{{Sfn|Gooptu|2010|p = 132}} For this version, Vasan re-shot some scenes and included a slightly different cast.{{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page = 93}} Among the notable differences between the Hindi and Tamil versions of the film, Pandit Indra and [[Aghajani Kashmeri|Agha Jani Kashmiri]] wrote the dialogue only for the Hindi version.<ref>''Chandralekha (Hindi) DVD''. Opening titles, at 1:11</ref> Indra was a lyricist for the Hindi version with [[Bharat Vyas]], while Subbu and Papanasam Sivan were lyricists for the Tamil version.<ref>''Chandralekha (Hindi) DVD''. Opening titles, at 1:16</ref> Rajeswara Rao, who composed the soundtrack for both versions, was assisted by Bal Krishna Kalla on the Hindi version. Parthasarathy and Vaidyanathan composed background music for the Hindi version without Das Gupta.<ref>''Chandralekha (Hindi) DVD''. Opening titles, at 1:21</ref>

Rajakumari, Radha and Ranjan reprised their roles in the Hindi version, but their characters{{mdash}}except for Rajakumari's character Chandralekha{{mdash}}were renamed. Radha's character Veerasimhan was known as Veer Singh in the Hindi version, and Ranjan's character Sasankan was renamed Shashank.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ncpamumbai.com/event/ncpa-flashback-chandralekha | title=NCPA Flashback &#124; Chandralekha | work=[[National Centre for the Performing Arts (India)]] | date=28 June 2013 | accessdate=22 September 2013 | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130908130904/http://www.ncpamumbai.com/event/ncpa-flashback-chandralekha | archivedate=22 September 2013 | location=Mumbai}}</ref> Of the other cast members, N. S. Krishnan, T. A. Madhuram, T. E. Krishnamachari, Pottai Krishnamoorthy and N. Seetharaman appeared only in the Tamil version, whereas Yashodhara Katju and H. K. Chopra appeared only in the Hindi version.{{Sfn|Rajadhyaksha|Willemen|1999|p = 310}} Nearly the entire cast were credited in the Tamil version,<ref name="tamil credits">''Chandralekha (Tamil) DVD''. Opening titles, from 0:45 to 1:20</ref> but only six people{{mdash}}Rajakumari, Radha, Ranjan, Sundari Bai, Katju and L. Narayana Rao{{mdash}}were credited in the Hindi version.<ref>''Chandralekha (Hindi) DVD''. Opening titles, at 0:45</ref>

==Legacy==

{{centered pull quote
 |<center>Sixty years ago the biggest box office hit of Tamil cinema was released. When made by the same studio in Hindi, it was so great a success that it opened up the theatres of the [[North India|North]] to films made in the [[South India|South]]. This is the story of the making of that film, ''Chandralekha'',</center>
 |author=Randor Guy, film historian and columnist<ref name="madras musings" />
}}

With the success of ''Chandralekha'', Vasan became known as one of the best directors in Indian cinema.<ref name="madras musings" /> Randor Guy later called Vasan the "Cecil B. DeMille of Tamil cinema",<ref name="Cecil" /> and called ''Chandralekha'' his "''[[magnum opus]]''".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/sri-kandha-leela-1938/article4564379.ece | title=Sri Kandha Leela 1938 | work=The Hindu | date=30 March 2013 | accessdate=8 October 2014 | author=Guy, Randor | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130701085814/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/sri-kandha-leela-1938/article4564379.ece | archivedate=1 July 2013}}</ref> According to S. Muthiah, Vasan "pioneered making South Indian films in English".<ref name="Cecil" /> He inspired producer [[A. V. Meiyappan]], who later became a "master at publicity".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2008-08-08/chennai/27895501_1_cinema-release-film-coffee-table-book | title=Kollywood turns to coffee-table books | work=The Times of India | date=8 August 2008 | accessdate=5 August 2013 | last=Ravi | first=Bhama Devi | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130718090154/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2008-08-08/chennai/27895501_1_cinema-release-film-coffee-table-book | archivedate=5 August 2013}}</ref> Gemini Studios published a book ''Campaign'' that described the [[making-of|making of]] ''Chandralekha''.{{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page = 94}} The film demonstrated that if a film was entertaining, it would be commercially successful.{{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page = 94}} The success of the Hindi version gave opportunities to South Indian film producers to market their Hindi films in North India.{{Sfn|Guy|1997|p = 251}} The publicity campaign for ''Chandralekha'' created such an impact that film producers in Bombay (now [[Mumbai]]) passed a resolution that there should be a limit imposed on advertisements for any film in periodicals.{{Sfn|Blamey|D'Souza|Dickey|2005|p = 57}} Vasan's ''[[Apoorva Sagodharargal (1949 film)|Apoorva Sagodharargal]]'' (1949) is often considered an unofficial sequel to ''Chandralekha''; it was also a major commercial success.<ref name="indolink" />{{Sfn|Rajadhyaksha|Willemen|1999|p = 312}}

''Chandralekha'' enhanced Rajakumari's and Ranjan's careers; both became popular throughout India after the film's release.<ref name="the hindu" /> Its climactic sword-fight scene was well received,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://hindu.com/thehindu/mp/2005/07/16/stories/2005071600550400.htm | title=Heroines of the past | work=The Hindu | date=16 July 2005 | accessdate=27 June 2013 | author=Vasanthan, J. | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130627073759/http://hindu.com/thehindu/mp/2005/07/16/stories/2005071600550400.htm | archivedate=27 June 2013}}</ref> and is thought to be the longest sword fight in Indian cinema.{{Sfn|Dwyer|Patel|2002|p = 144}} The drum-dance sequence is often considered the film's highlight;<ref name="the hindu" /><ref name="madras musings" /> later producers tried unsuccessfully to emulate it.{{Sfn|Gokulsing|Dissanayake|2004|p = 49}} Producer-director [[T. Rajendar]] said he drew inspiration from the drum-dance for a song sequence budgeted at {{INRConvert|10|m|year=1999}} in his 1999 film ''[[Monisha En Monalisa]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rediff.com/entertai/1998/oct/28ss.htm | title=Extravaganza | publisher=Rediff.com | date=28 October 1998 | accessdate=27 July 2014 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19991021205458/http://www.rediff.com/entertai/1998/oct/28ss.htm | archivedate=21 October 1999}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rediff.com/entertai/1998/dec/01ss.htm | title=Drama in reel life | publisher=Rediff.com | date=1 December 1998 | accessdate=27 July 2014 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19990208222021/http://www.rediff.com/entertai/1998/dec/01ss.htm | archivedate=8 February 1999}}</ref> Film historian Firoze Rangoonwalla ranked the Hindi version eighth in his list of "the top twenty films of Indian cinema".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article/Moving-Images/208416 | title=Moving Images | work=[[Outlook.com|Outlook]] | date=15 November 1999 | accessdate=24 July 2014 | last=Rangoonwalla | first=Firoze | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140724170040/http://www.outlookindia.com/article/Moving-Images/208416 | archivedate=24 July 2014}}</ref> ''Chandralekha'' was also a major influence on [[Kamalakara Kameswara Rao]]'s 1953 Telugu film ''[[Chandraharam]]'', featuring [[N. T. Rama Rao]].{{Sfn|Thoraval|2000|p = 350}} On 26 August 2004, a postage stamp featuring Vasan and the drum dance was released to commemorate the 35th anniversary of his death.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hindu.com/2004/08/27/stories/2004082702091300.htm | title=Stamp on S.S. Vasan released | work=The Hindu | date=27 August 2004 | accessdate=3 October 2013 | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20040911165749/http://www.hindu.com/2004/08/27/stories/2004082702091300.htm | archivedate=3 October 2013}}</ref>

In July 2007, S. R. Ashok Kumar of ''The Hindu'' asked eight Tamil film directors to list their all-time favourite Tamil films; two of them{{mdash}}[[J. Mahendran]] and [[K. Balachander]]{{mdash}}named ''Chandralekha''.<ref name = "KB and JM"/> Mahendran said, "If anybody tries to remake this black and white film, they will make a mockery of it".<ref name = "KB and JM">{{cite web | url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/filmmakers-favourites/article2272999.ece | title=Filmmakers' favourites | work=The Hindu | date=13 July 2007 | accessdate=13 August 2014 | author=Ashok Kumar, S. R. | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214004436/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/filmmakers-favourites/article2272999.ece | archivedate=14 December 2013}}</ref> Balachander said, "Just like ''[[Sivaji (film)|Sivaji]]'' today, people talked about ''Chandralekha'' in the past. Produced at a cost of Rs 30 lakhs (a huge sum at that time), it has grand sets. I have seen it 12 times."<ref name = "KB and JM"/> In December 2008, S. Muthiah said, "Given how spectacular it was{{mdash}}and the appreciation lavished on it from 1948 till well into the 1950s, which is when I caught up with it{{mdash}}I'm sure that if re-released, it would do better at the box office then most Tamil films today".<ref name="Cecil" /> In a 2011 interview with [[Indo-Asian News Service]] (IANS), South Indian Bollywood actor [[Vyjayanthimala]] said although people consider that she "paved the way" for other South Indian female actors in Hindi cinema, "the person who really opened the doors was S.S. Vasan". She said, "When [''Chandralekha'' was] released, it took the North by storm because by then they haven't seen that kind of lavish sets, costumes and splendour. So Vasan was the person who opened the door for Hindi films in the South."<ref>{{cite news | url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/vyjayanthimala-kumars-khans-bharatanatyam-dancer/1/152150.html | title=Camera does wonders today: Vyjayanthimala | work=[[India Today]] | date=21 September 2011 | agency=[[Indo Asian News Service|IANS]] | accessdate=27 September 2013 | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110921210242/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/vyjayanthimala-kumars-khans-bharatanatyam-dancer/1/152150.html | archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>

''Chandralekha'' was K. Ramnoth's last film for Gemini Studios. Although he is often credited with shooting the drum-dance sequence, Ramnoth left the studio in August 1947, before the sequence had been conceived.<ref name="Rohini" /> Director [[Singeetham Srinivasa Rao]] told film critic [[Baradwaj Rangan]] he disliked ''Chandralekha'' when he first saw it, realising that it was a classic only after 25 years, "a fact that the audiences realised in just two minutes".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://baradwajrangan.wordpress.com/2011/11/04/lights-camera-conversation-crouched-around-a-campfire-storyteller/ | title=Lights, Camera, Conversation&nbsp;..."Crouched around a campfire storyteller" | publisher=Baradwajrangan.wordpress.com | date=4 November 2011 | accessdate=17 September 2013 | author=[[Baradwaj Rangan|Rangan, Baradwaj]] | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20111107004332/http://baradwajrangan.wordpress.com/2011/11/04/lights-camera-conversation-crouched-around-a-campfire-storyteller/ | archivedate=17 September 2013}}</ref> G. Dhananjayan told ''[[The Times of India]]'', "When you talk of black and white films, you cannot resist mentioning the 1948 epic ''Chandralekha''".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-02/news-interviews/31114286_1_tamil-cinema-tamil-film-white-films | title=Black and white films in Kollywood | work=The Times of India | date=2 March 2012 | accessdate=7 August 2013 | author=Suganth, M. | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130807134005/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-02/news-interviews/31114286_1_tamil-cinema-tamil-film-white-films | archivedate=7 August 2013}}</ref> In April 2012, Rediff.com included the film in its list "The A to Z of Tamil Cinema" and said it "boasted an ensemble cast, great production values and a story that ensured it became a blockbuster all over India, the first of its kind".<ref name="a to z">{{cite web | url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-south-the-a-to-z-of-tamil-cinema/20120418.htm?print=true | title=Special: The A to Z of Tamil Cinema | publisher=Rediff.com | date=18 April 2012 | accessdate=21 July 2014 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130703080548/http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-south-the-a-to-z-of-tamil-cinema/20120418.htm?print=true | archivedate=3 July 2013}}</ref>

''Chandralekha'' has been screened at many film festivals; it was screened in December 2012 at the 10th [[Chennai International Film Festival]], which was a tribute to 100 years of Indian cinema.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/chen-metroplus/showcase-of-the-best/article4160220.ece | title=Showcase of the best | work=The Hindu | date=3 December 2012 | accessdate=6 August 2013 | author=[[Sudhish Kamath|Kamath, Sudhish]] | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130704093009/http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/chen-metroplus/showcase-of-the-best/article4160220.ece | archivedate=6 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.chennaifilmfest.com/ciff_10.html | title=Highlights of 10th CHENNAI INTERNATIONAL FILM FESTIVAL | publisher=[[Chennai International Film Festival]] | accessdate=8 October 2014 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131122011130/http://www.chennaifilmfest.com/ciff_10.html | archivedate=22 November 2013}}</ref> To mark the same anniversary, it was also screened in April 2013 at the Centenary Film Festival, which was organised by India's Ministry of Information and Broadcasting and [[National Film Archive of India|National Film Archive]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/329283/films-saw-all-over-100.html | title=Films that saw it all over 100 years | work=Deccan Herald | date=30 April 2013 | accessdate=8 October 2013 | last=Rakheja | first=Henna | archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6KD0MVkTT | archivedate=30 April 2013}}</ref> In 2014, ''Chandralekha'' was one of eight Indian films{{efn|The other seven Indian films were ''[[Awara (1951 film)|Awara]]'' (1951), ''[[Do Bigha Zamin]]'' (1953), ''[[Pyaasa]]'' (1957), ''[[Mother India]]'' (1957), ''[[Ajantrik]]'' (1958), ''[[Madhumati]]'' (1958) and ''[[Kaagaz Ke Phool]]'' (1959).<ref>{{cite news | url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2014-06-30/news/50974380_1_mother-india-celluloid-man-shivendra-singh-dungarpur | title='Endangered' Indian classic cinema at Italy film festival | work=The Economic Times | date=30 June 2014 | agency=[[Press Trust of India]] | accessdate=27 August 2014 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140724171854/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2014-06-30/news/50974380_1_mother-india-celluloid-man-shivendra-singh-dungarpur | archivedate=24 July 2014}}</ref>}} that were screened at the 28th edition of the Italian film festival [[Il Cinema Ritrovato]], as a part of "The Golden 50s: India's Endangered Classics"{{mdash}}the first Indian cinema retrospective at the festival.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.davidbordwell.net/blog/2014/07/12/28267/ | title=Il Cinema Ritrovato: Strands from the 1950s and 1960s | publisher=Davidbordwell.net | date=12 July 2014 | accessdate=24 July 2014 | author=[[David Bordwell|Bordwell, David]] | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140717102151/http://www.davidbordwell.net/blog/2014/07/12/28267/ | archivedate=17 July 2014}}</ref>

